        "title": "IAM Users: Detailed Explanation",
        "content": "IAM Users represent individual people or applications interacting with AWS.\n\n*   Each user has unique security credentials (password, access keys).\n*   Users can be assigned specific permissions to access AWS resources.\n*   Best practice: Enable multi-factor authentication (MFA) for enhanced security."
      },
      {
        "title": "IAM Groups: Detailed Explanation",
        "content": "IAM Groups are collections of IAM users that are assigned identical permissions.\n\n*   Groups simplify permission management by applying policies to multiple users at once.\n*   Adding or removing a user from a group automatically updates their permissions.\n*   Groups do not have permissions themselves; they inherit permissions from attached policies."
      },
      {
        "title": "IAM Policies: Detailed Explanation",
        "content": "IAM Policies define the permissions granted to IAM users, groups, or roles.\n\n*   Policies are written in JSON format and specify allowed or denied actions on AWS resources.\n*   Policies can be attached directly to users, groups, or roles.\n*   AWS provides pre-defined managed policies, or you can create custom policies tailored to your needs.\n*   IAM lets you manage users, groups, and roles to define granular permissions."
      }
    ]
  }
